<paragraph blockId="6.[229,678,1488,1576]" box="[251,656,1552,1576]" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">
Genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Stierlin, 1853" authorityName="Stierlin" authorityYear="1853" box="[330,656,1552,1576]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Dichotrachelus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[330,499,1552,1576]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">Dichotrachelus</emphasis>
Stierlin, 1853
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="6" pageNumber="21" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,756,1600,2078]" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">
The monophyly of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stierlin" authorityYear="1853" box="[471,635,1600,1623]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Dichotrachelus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[471,635,1600,1623]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">Dichotrachelus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is strongly supported in both our analyses (
<figureCitation box="[498,562,1633,1657]" captionStart="Fig. 1" captionStartId="3.[151,186,1908,1929]" captionTargetBox="[155,1408,263,1896]" captionTargetId="graphics@3.[544,992,642,2095]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Best Maximum Likelihood tree as selected by MEGA) based on COI sequences of 142 samples of Curculionoidea (Chrysomelidae obtained by using MEGA 6. Values (over 50 %) of bootstrap support from 100 nodes." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1040870/files/figure.svg" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
, Supp. 1). Within this genus, there is definitely more hidden diversity in these relatively immobile typically alpine living species distributed from the Rif Mountains of Morocco to the Carpathians in the east, with a speciation centre in the arc of the Alps. The species are ecologically bound either to mosses (“old” lineages) or 
<taxonomicName box="[606,756,1827,1850]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Saxifragaceae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="6" pageNumber="21" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Saxifragaceae</taxonomicName>
(“derived” lineages) (
<bibRefCitation author="Meregalli M. &amp; Monguzzi R. &amp; Klass K-D. &amp; Cervella P. &amp; Kahlen M." box="[399,664,1859,1884]" journalOrPublisher="Arthropod systematics and phylogeny" pageId="6" pageNumber="21" pagination="323 - 332" part="73" refString="Meregalli M., Monguzzi R., Klass K-D., Cervella P. &amp; Kahlen M. 2015. Dichotrachelus pesarinii sp. n., a missing link between the species from the central and the western southern Alps (Coleoptera: Curculionidae: Cyclominae). Arthropod systematics and phylogeny 73 (2): 323 - 332." title="Dichotrachelus pesarinii sp. n., a missing link between the species from the central and the western southern Alps (Coleoptera: Curculionidae: Cyclominae)" type="journal article" year="2015">
Meregalli 
<emphasis box="[521,577,1859,1884]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">et al</emphasis>
., 2015
</bibRefCitation>
). Based on COI sequences, we found at least in three species considerable differences among the samples, promoting the hypotheses of existing cryptic species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,756,1600,2078]" lastBlockId="6.[831,1437,258,2078]" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">
Data from 
<emphasis box="[267,434,1989,2013]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">D. koziorowiczi</emphasis>
Desbrochers des 
<bibRefCitation author="Desbrochers des Loges J." box="[624,756,1990,2014]" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="6" pageNumber="21" pagination="118 - 119" part="1873" refString="Desbrochers des Loges J. 1873. [new taxa] Bulletin de la Societe Entomologique de France 1873: 118 - 119." title="[new taxa] Bulletin de la Societe Entomologique de France" type="journal article" year="1873">Loges, 1873</bibRefCitation>
from two localities on Corsica (one in the North at Col de Verghio; the other in the South on Monte Calva) show that two taxa (K2 distance: 0.067; 
<tableCitation box="[1208,1289,258,283]" captionStart="Tables 1 - 8" captionStartId="11.[151,213,258,279]" captionText="Tables 1 - 8: COI Kimura 2 - Parameter genetic distances for a set of selected samples used in the present study. See the main text for further details." pageId="6" pageNumber="21">Table 2</tableCitation>
) are likely to occur on this island, instead of one at present described species. Only the examination of the type specimen(s) will help to resolve this issue, as no precise type locality on the island has been given by 
<bibRefCitation author="Desbrochers des Loges J." box="[1173,1387,386,411]" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="6" pageNumber="21" pagination="118 - 119" part="1873" refString="Desbrochers des Loges J. 1873. [new taxa] Bulletin de la Societe Entomologique de France 1873: 118 - 119." title="[new taxa] Bulletin de la Societe Entomologique de France" type="journal article" year="1873">Desbrochers (1873)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[831,1437,258,2078]" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">
Similarly, with the 
<emphasis box="[1075,1234,418,443]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">D. maculosus</emphasis>
Fairmaire, 1869 
<emphasis box="[831,840,452,475]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">-</emphasis>
species group, where specimens of 
<emphasis box="[1228,1376,450,475]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">D. maculosus</emphasis>
from rather isolated populations in the Vercors, at the western border of the main distribution area, differ from those from the Swiss Prealps (K2 distance: 0.026).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[831,1437,258,2078]" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">
Also in the 
<emphasis box="[958,1071,580,603]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">D. augusti</emphasis>
F. Solari, 1946 
<emphasis box="[1244,1253,580,603]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">-</emphasis>
species complex, more morphological diversity was discovered (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Germann C." box="[831,1026,643,667]" journalOrPublisher="Contributions to Natural History" pageId="6" pageNumber="21" pagination="1 - 21" part="17" refString="Germann C. 2011 b. Review of the Dichotrachelus alpestris Stierlin, 1878 species group with evidence for a species complex of D. augusti F. Solari, 1946, and D. sondereggeri sp. nov. from Switzerland (Coleoptera, Curculionidae). Contributions to Natural History 17: 1 - 21." title="Review of the Dichotrachelus alpestris Stierlin, 1878 species group with evidence for a species complex of D. augusti F. Solari, 1946, and D. sondereggeri sp. nov. from Switzerland (Coleoptera, Curculionidae)" type="journal article" year="2011" yearSuffix="b">Germann, 2011b</bibRefCitation>
), here corroborated partly by the detected genetic diversity. The rather isolated population from the Saas Valley (sample 89) differs genetically considerably (K2 distance: 0.115!) from those of samples from the Grand St. Bernard and Col de Balme regions at the Swiss-Italian and Swiss-French border, which is indeed surprising, as it is surprisingly not reflected in their morphology, whereas 
<taxonomicName authority="Germann, 2011" authorityName="Germann" authorityYear="2011" box="[1077,1436,867,892]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Dichotrachelus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sondereggeri">
<emphasis box="[1077,1255,867,892]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">D. sondereggeri</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Germann C." box="[1266,1436,868,892]" journalOrPublisher="Mitteilungen der Schweizerischen Entomologischen Gesellschaft" pageId="6" pageNumber="21" pagination="155 - 169" part="84" refString="Germann C. 2011 a. Supplement zur Checkliste der Russelkafer der Schweiz (Coleoptera, Curculionoidea). Mitteilungen der Schweizerischen Entomologischen Gesellschaft 84: 155 - 169." title="Supplement zur Checkliste der Russelkafer der Schweiz (Coleoptera, Curculionoidea)" type="journal article" year="2011">Germann, 2011</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
shows differences, but solely results in a genetic distance of 0.016 compared with the western populations of 
<emphasis box="[831,943,965,988]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">D. augusti</emphasis>
. Furthermore, the different forms of the penis (
<bibRefCitation author="Germann C." box="[839,1024,995,1020]" journalOrPublisher="Contributions to Natural History" pageId="6" pageNumber="21" pagination="1 - 21" part="17" refString="Germann C. 2011 b. Review of the Dichotrachelus alpestris Stierlin, 1878 species group with evidence for a species complex of D. augusti F. Solari, 1946, and D. sondereggeri sp. nov. from Switzerland (Coleoptera, Curculionidae). Contributions to Natural History 17: 1 - 21." title="Review of the Dichotrachelus alpestris Stierlin, 1878 species group with evidence for a species complex of D. augusti F. Solari, 1946, and D. sondereggeri sp. nov. from Switzerland (Coleoptera, Curculionidae)" type="journal article" year="2011" yearSuffix="b">Germann, 2011b</bibRefCitation>
) detected in the western populations of 
<emphasis box="[868,988,1029,1052]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">D. augusti</emphasis>
in turn are not supported by relevant differences in the COI (0.002). However, to definitely delimit and show more solid insights into the systematics of the 
<emphasis box="[906,1021,1125,1148]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">D. augusti</emphasis>
-species complex we would still have to include samples from the type locality of 
<emphasis box="[1323,1437,1157,1180]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">D. augusti</emphasis>
from around Champoluc in Valle d’Aosta. Additionally, the highly specialised habitat demands of the 
<emphasis box="[1316,1428,1221,1244]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">D. augusti</emphasis>
- species complex might explain for the genetic differences between geographically close populations: all species of this complex live in mosses growing in alpine scree slopes, an unusual and certainly underestimated habitat, less in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[908,1016,1380,1403]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Carabidae</taxonomicName>
(where exciting discoveries have been reported e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Molenda R." box="[980,1149,1412,1435]" journalOrPublisher="Verhandlungen des Naturwissenschaftlichen Vereins Hamburg Neue Folge" pageId="6" pageNumber="21" pagination="5 - 93" part="35" refString="Molenda R. 1996. Zoogeographische Bedeutung Kaltluft erzeugender Blockhalden im ausseralpinen Mitteleuropa. Verhandlungen des Naturwissenschaftlichen Vereins Hamburg Neue Folge 35: 5 - 93." title="Zoogeographische Bedeutung Kaltluft erzeugender Blockhalden im ausseralpinen Mitteleuropa" type="journal article" year="1996">Molenda, 1996</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Molenda R. &amp; Gude M." box="[1164,1433,1412,1437]" editor="Konold W." journalOrPublisher="Zoology" pageId="6" pageNumber="21" part="9" refString="Molenda R., Gude M. 2003. Felsen, Block- und Schutthalden, Blockmeere [pp. 1 - 5]. In: Konold W., Bocke R., Hampicke U. (eds). Handbuch Naturschutz und Landschaftspflege. 9. Erganzte Lieferung, Kapitel XI- 2.27. ecomed, Landsberg." title="Felsen, Block- und Schutthalden, Blockmeere [pp. 1 - 5]" type="journal volume" volumeTitle="Handbuch Naturschutz und Landschaftspflege" year="2003">Molenda &amp; Gude, 2003</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Huber C. &amp; Molenda R." box="[831,1111,1444,1469]" journalOrPublisher="Contributions to Natural History" pageId="6" pageNumber="21" pagination="1 - 28" part="4" refString="Huber C. &amp; Molenda R. 2004. Nebria (Nebriola) praegensis sp. nov., ein Periglazialrelikt im Sud-Schwarzwald / Deutschland, mit Beschreibung der Larven (Insecta, Coleoptera, Carabidae). Contributions to Natural History 4: 1 - 28." title="Nebria (Nebriola) praegensis sp. nov., ein Periglazialrelikt im Sud-Schwarzwald / Deutschland, mit Beschreibung der Larven (Insecta, Coleoptera, Carabidae)" type="journal article" year="2004">Huber &amp; Molenda, 2004</bibRefCitation>
), or 
<taxonomicName authority="(Molenda, 1999)" authorityName="Molenda" authorityYear="1999" baseAuthorityName="Molenda" baseAuthorityYear="1999" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">
Staphylinidae (
<bibRefCitation author="Molenda R." journalOrPublisher="Zoology" pageId="6" pageNumber="21" pagination="85" part="102" refString="Molenda R. 1999. Leptusa simoni Eppelsheim, 1878 (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae) a zoogeographical analysis of an indicator organism of air-conditioned scree slopes. Zoology 102 (Supplement II): 85." title="Leptusa simoni Eppelsheim, 1878 (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae) a zoogeographical analysis of an indicator organism of air-conditioned scree slopes" type="journal article" year="1999">Molenda, 1999</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, but more in weevils where hardly any research has been done, and a promising field for investigations lies idle (Nikolai Yunakov, personal comm.). The alpine scree slopes thereafter can be seen as islands for the populations of the 
<emphasis box="[912,1030,1606,1629]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">D. augusti</emphasis>
-complex, where gene exchange via migrating individuals across alpine grasslands and glaciers might be very limited. This specific case once more shows that samples from populations of a species, at least if we deal with low mobile species, should be chosen very carefully.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[831,1437,258,2078]" lastBlockId="8.[151,756,258,377]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">
The samples of species assigned to the 
<emphasis box="[1316,1437,1797,1821]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">D. rudenispecies</emphasis>
group, based on a similar external morphology and male genitalia with a prolonged, laterally flattened tip of penis, also clustered together (
<taxonomicName authority="Stierlin, 1853" authorityName="Stierlin" authorityYear="1853" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Dichotrachelus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rudeni">
<emphasis box="[1237,1342,1893,1918]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">D. rudeni</emphasis>
Stierlin, 1853
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Stierlin, 1857" authorityName="Stierlin" authorityYear="1857" box="[899,1159,1925,1950]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Dichotrachelus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imhoffi">
<emphasis box="[899,1006,1925,1950]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">D. imhoffi</emphasis>
Stierlin, 1857
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Daniel &amp; Daniel, 1898" authorityName="Daniel &amp; Daniel" authorityYear="1898" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Dichotrachelus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variegatus">
<emphasis box="[1212,1358,1927,1950]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">D. variegatus</emphasis>
Daniel &amp; Daniel, 1898
</taxonomicName>
) and therefore support the outcomes from previous morphological investigations (
<tableCitation box="[1335,1423,1989,2014]" captionStart="Tables 1 - 8" captionStartId="11.[151,213,258,279]" captionText="Tables 1 - 8: COI Kimura 2 - Parameter genetic distances for a set of selected samples used in the present study. See the main text for further details." pageId="6" pageNumber="21">Table 2</tableCitation>
). The samples of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stierlin" authorityYear="1853" box="[1008,1112,2022,2046]" class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Dichotrachelus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rudeni">
<emphasis box="[1008,1112,2022,2046]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="21">D. rudeni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
cluster all together with high bootstrap support (ML 99%, respectively NJ 98%), although there is some herogeneity in it with sample 109 from the eastern border of the distribution near Disentis (sample 109) differing most from the others (0.010 to 0.016).
</paragraph>
